                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout style="vertical" rend="arris_up">The stone is inscribed with <q>two fragmentary ogam inscriptions. The first is on the left angle (A/D) near the top and reads vertically upwards. The second is in a similar position on the right angle (A/B) and reads vertically downwards</q>. There is also a <q>roman-letter, Latin inscription set horizontally in eight lines</q> (Edwards 2007, 294).</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>The ogham strokes which Edwards (2007, 294) describes as <q>finely and lightly incised</q> appear to have been <rs type="execution" key="chiselled" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/1.html">chiselled</rs>. The Latin inscription is medium-incised and is in book-script, exhibiting letters with <q>triangular or bifid serifs</q> (Edwards 2007, 294). <q>There are variations in the forms of some letters. ET, EX and AE are ligatures; GN and TI are conjoined... An inscription remarkable for the evenness of its book-script. The letter-forms are carefully controlled and tend to be made as square as possible, with several geometric forms (F, G, N, S, U)</q> (Edwards 2007, 294-298).
                                <height></height>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
                    </physDesc>
